issue.title: FindSodium.cmake doesn't find shared libsodium
issue.body:
FindSodium.cmake doesn't find the libsodium shared library on my Linux system. I was able to get it to work by commenting out some of the static library detection like so:
```
--- FindSodium.cmake.orig	2022-11-29 22:22:39.845951870 -0500
+++ FindSodium.cmake.worksmin	2022-11-29 22:51:52.737827922 -0500
@@ -80,28 +80,28 @@
         pkg_check_modules(sodium_PKG QUIET libsodium)
     endif()
 
-    if(sodium_USE_STATIC_LIBS)
-        foreach(_libname ${sodium_PKG_STATIC_LIBRARIES})
-            if (NOT _libname MATCHES "^lib.*\\.a$") # ignore strings already ending with .a
-                list(INSERT sodium_PKG_STATIC_LIBRARIES 0 "lib${_libname}.a")
-            endif()
-        endforeach()
-        list(REMOVE_DUPLICATES sodium_PKG_STATIC_LIBRARIES)
+#    if(sodium_USE_STATIC_LIBS)
+#        foreach(_libname ${sodium_PKG_STATIC_LIBRARIES})
+#            if (NOT _libname MATCHES "^lib.*\\.a$") # ignore strings already ending with .a
+#                list(INSERT sodium_PKG_STATIC_LIBRARIES 0 "lib${_libname}.a")
+#            endif()
+#        endforeach()
+#        list(REMOVE_DUPLICATES sodium_PKG_STATIC_LIBRARIES)
 
         # if pkgconfig for libsodium doesn't provide
         # static lib info, then override PKG_STATIC here..
-        if (NOT sodium_PKG_STATIC_FOUND)
-            set(sodium_PKG_STATIC_LIBRARIES libsodium.a)
-        endif()
+#        if (NOT sodium_PKG_STATIC_FOUND)
+#            set(sodium_PKG_STATIC_LIBRARIES libsodium.a)
+#        endif()
 
-        set(XPREFIX sodium_PKG_STATIC)
-    else()
+#        set(XPREFIX sodium_PKG_STATIC)
+#    else()
         if (NOT sodium_PKG_FOUND)
             set(sodium_PKG_LIBRARIES sodium)
         endif()
 
         set(XPREFIX sodium_PKG)
-    endif()
+#    endif()
 
     find_path(sodium_INCLUDE_DIR sodium.h
         HINTS ${${XPREFIX}_INCLUDE_DIRS}
```
After these changes, it finds libsodium.so and compiles without issue.

Thank you

issue.title: padframe: rotating the corners moves them outside of the chip area
issue.body:
When I define out corner padcell using

```TCL
define_pad_cell \
    -name corner \
    -corner \
    -cell_name corner \
    -orient { ll R0 lr R90 ur R180 ul R270 } \
    -physical_only
```

it's in the correct position but rotated incorrectly. When I try to adjust the rotation by 180° as follows:

```TCL
define_pad_cell \
    -name corner \
    -corner \
    -cell_name corner \
    -orient { ll R180 lr R270 ur R0 ul R90 } \
    -physical_only
```

the cell is rotated correctly, but positioned outside of the chip area:

![corner-rotation-bug](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5029529/189156662-8f381782-ceac-4fb4-b54b-b6b306172d55.png)

I guess the origin of the cell needs to be adjusted/is adjusted incorrectly after rotation.

comment.body: Can confirm this is fixed, thanks!

issue.title: Examples of usage
issue.body:
Could you offer some examples of usage, or document clients that use this library.

Thanks

comment.body:
Your timing is a bit unlucky in that regard - this library has been reworked recently and existing client implementations were not updated to use the new code yet, thus Libervia is the only up-to-date implementation. The "gorgeous, typed, async modern python" (:D) in `slixmpp/omemo` uses the pre-rework code of this library and will soon be updated to use the new reworked codebase. (Ppjet6 is the maintainer of `slixmpp/omemo`, I'm sure he'll enjoy your nice words). The rework will seriously simplify the code, since the rework aims to make OMEMO accessible to developers that don't have a deep understanding of the required cryptography and protocol flows etc.

One detail that might help with your evaluation: this is the only library that supports the newest version of the OMEMO specification. I'd highly recommend new OMEMO client implementations to support the most recent version of the spec right away, as the first existing implementations are slowly being upgraded to support it as well.

And now for a bit of shameless self-promotion: I guarantee with some confidence that this is your lowest-headache shot at equipping your client with OMEMO. There are no other "modern" OMEMO implementations I am aware of, especially if you're looking for fully typed, clean Python 3. I'd be happy to work closely with you if you decide to go with python-omemo. You can ping me privately on XMPP (tim@mailbox.bz) or maybe even better in the jdev MUC (jdev@muc.xmpp.org) where other client devs might chime in with recommendations too.

issue.title: Examples of usage
issue.body:
Could you offer some examples of usage, or document clients that use this library.

Thanks

comment.body:
Hey, adding to what @Ppjet6 already recommended:

please refer to [Getting Started](https://github.com/Syndace/python-omemo/blob/main/docs/getting_started.rst) in the documentation for instructions on setting up the library for your client (sorry, I don't have the rendered doc online anywhere yet. Will take care of that in a minute.). I have just added a small example of how you could implement BTBV in [`examples/btbv_session_manager.py`](https://github.com/Syndace/python-omemo/blob/main/examples/btbv_session_manager.py) as well. Generally, the library comes with extensive docstrings in the code. If the given information isn't enough to get you started, I recommend to skim through the code in [`omemo/session_manager.py`](https://github.com/Syndace/python-omemo/blob/main/omemo/session_manager.py) and read through the doc strings.

I can't really add a lot of general examples, since the usage/implementation of python-omemo largely depends on the client library used. If you have any specific questions, feel free to ask them here.

issue.title: padframe: rotating the corners moves them outside of the chip area
issue.body:
When I define out corner padcell using

```TCL
define_pad_cell \
    -name corner \
    -corner \
    -cell_name corner \
    -orient { ll R0 lr R90 ur R180 ul R270 } \
    -physical_only
```

it's in the correct position but rotated incorrectly. When I try to adjust the rotation by 180° as follows:

```TCL
define_pad_cell \
    -name corner \
    -corner \
    -cell_name corner \
    -orient { ll R180 lr R270 ur R0 ul R90 } \
    -physical_only

![corner-rotation-bug](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5029529/189156662-8f381782-ceac-4fb4-b54b-b6b306172d55.png)

I guess the origin of the cell needs to be adjusted/is adjusted incorrectly after rotation.

comment.body:
Your timing is a bit unlucky in that regard - this library has been reworked recently and existing client implementations were not updated to use the new code yet, thus Libervia is the only up-to-date implementation. The "gorgeous, typed, async modern python" (:D) in `slixmpp/omemo` uses the pre-rework code of this library and will soon be updated to use the new reworked codebase. (Ppjet6 is the maintainer of `slixmpp/omemo`, I'm sure he'll enjoy your nice words). The rework will seriously simplify the code, since the rework aims to make OMEMO accessible to developers that don't have a deep understanding of the required cryptography and protocol flows etc.

One detail that might help with your evaluation: this is the only library that supports the newest version of the OMEMO specification. I'd highly recommend new OMEMO client implementations to support the most recent version of the spec right away, as the first existing implementations are slowly being upgraded to support it as well.

And now for a bit of shameless self-promotion: I guarantee with some confidence that this is your lowest-headache shot at equipping your client with OMEMO. There are no other "modern" OMEMO implementations I am aware of, especially if you're looking for fully typed, clean Python 3. I'd be happy to work closely with you if you decide to go with python-omemo. You can ping me privately on XMPP (tim@mailbox.bz) or maybe even better in the jdev MUC (jdev@muc.xmpp.org) where other client devs might chime in with recommendations too.

Will take care of that in a minute.). I have just added a small example of how you could implement BTBV in [`examples/btbv_session_manager.py`](https://github.com/Syndace/python-omemo/blob/main/examples/btbv_session_manager.py) as well. Generally, the library comes with extensive docstrings in the code. If the given information isn't enough to get you started, I recommend to skim through the code in [`omemo/session_manager.py`](https://github.com/Syndace/python-omemo/blob/main/omemo/session_manager.py) and read through the doc strings.
